|valign="top"|[[File:Arcosolium.jpg|thumb|100px|One of the ornately decorated 4th century arcosolia in the [[hypogeum]] of Via Dino Compagni (Via Latina Catacomb) in Rome. The figure of the frescoes is [[Terra Mater|Tellus]], the Roman goddess of the earth, after whom this tomb is also named.]]
|valign="top"|[[File:Sigüenza - Sepulcro de Martín Vázquez de Arce.jpg|thumb|100px|The 15th-century arcosolium of Martín Vázquez de Arce, in the wall of the Cathedral of [[Sigüenza|Sigüenza, Spain]]. Like most post-Roman era arcosolia, this tomb is above ground. The alabaster figure on the lid of the sarcophagus is the famous ''el doncel de Sigüenza'', "the boy of Sigüenza".]]
|}
An '''arcosolium''', plural '''arcosolia''', is an arched recess used as a place of entombment. The word is from Latin ''arcus'', "arch", and ''solium'', "throne" (literally: "place of state") or post-classical "[[sarcophagus]]".{{dubious|What is it supposed to mean, "place of state"? And what is the connection to "sarcophagus? Mess...|date=August 2018}}

Early arcosolia were [[cut from the living rock|carved out of the living rock]] in [[catacomb]]s. In the very earliest of these, the arched recess was cut to ground level. Then a low wall would be built in the front, leaving a trough (the ''cubiculum'', "chamber") in which to place the body. A flat stone slab would then cover the chamber containing the body, thus sealing it. The stone slab occasionally also served as an altar, especially for Christians, who celebrated Mass on them. In the later arcosolia, the arched recess was carved out to about waist height. Then the masons cut downwards to make the chamber into which the corpse would be placed. In effect, the trough was then a sarcophagus with living rock on five of its six faces. As before, a flat stone slab would then seal the ''cubiculum''. 

From the 13th century onwards, and continuing into the [[Renaissance]], arcosolia were built above ground, particularly in the walls of churches. In these post-Roman era recesses, which were built of brick and marble, the sarcophagi are usually separate from the arch. These tombs are highly ornamented in the styles of those periods;<ref>Cross, F. L. (ed.) (1957) ''The Oxford Dictionary of the Christian Church''. Oxford U. P.; p. 80</ref> the [[Flamboyant|Flamboyant Gothic]], [[Plateresque]], and [[High Renaissance]] styles are all represented.

